<TITLE> Indian fin min says slow farm growth a worry </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 BANGALORE, June 7 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Sluggish agriculture growth is a concern even as the overall economy expands at a fast pace, Indian Finance Minister Palaniappan Chidambaram said on Thursday. Nearly two-thirds of India's more than a billion people depend on the farm sector for their livelihood, but agriculture contributes only about 18 percent of India's gross domestic product. "We are today a trillion dollar economy. However, we are concerned about the slow rate of growth of agriculture," Chidambaram said at a biotechnology summit in the southern Indian city of Bangalore. India's economy grew 9.4 percent in the fiscal year that ended in March, its fastest rate in 18 years. But agriculture grew just 2.7 percent, while services expanded 11 percent and industry rose 10.9 percent. The production of wheat and rice has remained stagnant for the past 10 years, Chidambaram said
